===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
Inconclusive. In the oracle bone and bronze scripts, the most common form was {{Han compound|日|東|t1=sun|t2=bag; east}}. Here are a few proposed interpretations as an {{liushu|ic|nocap=1}}:
* {{zh-l|*日}} was sometimes replaced with {{zh-l|*田}}, so {{w|Qiu Xigui}} thinks that it may be the original character of {{och-l|糧|grain field}}.
* {{w|Yu Xingwu}} interprets it as measuring something under the sun.
* {{w|Guo Moruo}} interprets it as the sun rising in the east – original character of {{och-l|亮}}.
* Huang Dekuan suspects the {{och-l|*日}} is actually {{och-l|昜}} as the phonetic component.

''{{w|Shuowen}}'' interprets this as a {{Han compound|曏|重|ls=psc|c1=p|c2=s|t2=weight; heavy|nocap=1}}.

===Etymology===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*k-raŋ||to count, to measure}} (STEDT under *(g/k)raŋ; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). Cognate to {{cog|bo|བགྲང||to count}}, {{cog|klr|'''ʾkhran'''-ne}}, {{cog|my|ခြင်||to measure capacity}}, {{cog|nuf|xɹɯ³¹||to count}}.

Pronunciation 2 is possibly an *''-s''-suffixed [[exopassive]] derivation of Pronunciation 1; thus it means "what is measured → a measure" and is cognate to {{cog|bo|གྲངས||t=number}} (see also {{zh-ref|Unger (1983)}})

